import{c as t,Q as o,j as a,m as r}from"./chunks/framework.DibtWjA6.js";const g=JSON.parse('{"title":"wshobson/agents — debrief","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"case-studies/2026-04-18-wshobson-agents-learnings.md","filePath":"case-studies/2026-04-18-wshobson-agents-learnings.md","lastUpdated":null}'),n={name:"case-studies/2026-04-18-wshobson-agents-learnings.md"};function s(i,e,d,l,h,c){return o(),a("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[r('<h1 id="wshobson-agents-—-debrief" tabindex="-1">wshobson/agents — debrief <a class="header-anchor" href="#wshobson-agents-—-debrief" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;wshobson/agents — debrief&quot;">​</a></h1><p>Companion to <a href="./2026-04-18-wshobson-agents"><code>2026-04-18-wshobson-agents.md</code></a>. That one is the public artifact, written by the automated pipeline. This one is the internal debrief: what the engagement taught us about NLPM itself, what we got wrong, and what should change before the next run.</p><p>Audience: xiaolai and anyone else building contribution pipelines.</p><h2 id="the-honest-timeline" tabindex="-1">The honest timeline <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-honest-timeline" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The honest timeline&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The auto-generated article reports &quot;five PRs merged in 12 seconds.&quot; That&#39;s accurate but misleading in isolation. Full wall clock:</p><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Phase</th><th>Start</th><th>End</th><th>Duration</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>NLPM audit</td><td>2026-04-17 12:24:19</td><td>12:33:30</td><td><strong>9m 11s</strong> (active compute)</td></tr><tr><td>Gap — batch processor poll</td><td>12:33:30</td><td>12:49:59</td><td>16m 29s (idle)</td></tr><tr><td>NLPM contribute (5 PRs)</td><td>12:49:59</td><td>12:56:24</td><td><strong>6m 25s</strong> (active compute)</td></tr><tr><td>Maintainer response latency</td><td>12:55:28 (last PR open)</td><td>17:15:22 (first merge)</td><td><strong>4h 19m 54s</strong> (idle)</td></tr><tr><td>Merge burst (5 PRs)</td><td>17:15:22</td><td>17:15:35</td><td><strong>13 seconds</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p>So: ~15 min of active compute on our side, ~31 min wall clock from onboarding to PRs live, then 4h 20m of nothing, then 13 seconds of merging. &quot;Instant&quot; it was not. &quot;Fastest we&#39;ve seen&quot; is true only inside a narrow window.</p><p>Estimated Claude-token cost for the audit + contribute: <strong>$0.25–$0.80</strong> (Sonnet tier, ~30K–50K tokens across both calls). Cheap; the polling gap is more expensive than the compute.</p><h2 id="the-agentic-handshake" tabindex="-1">The agentic handshake <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-agentic-handshake" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The agentic handshake&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Evidence both sides were running pipelines:</p><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Signal</th><th>What it suggests</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Merge cadence 17:15:<strong>22, :25, :29, :32, :35</strong> — 3s per PR</td><td>Scripted merge loop, not tab-clicking</td></tr><tr><td>5 identical comments: <em>&quot;Thanks @xiaolai — merged. Appreciate the NLPM audit catching these silent registration failures.&quot;</em></td><td>Template, not typing</td></tr><tr><td>Zero inline review comments across all 5 PRs</td><td>No per-PR human reasoning</td></tr><tr><td><code>validate.yml</code> CI is JSON + structural checks only</td><td>Deterministic green-light rubric an agent can trust</td></tr><tr><td>Prior commits <code>Co-authored-by: Claude Sonnet 4.6</code> on <code>main</code></td><td>Maintainer already dogfoods Claude for their own work</td></tr><tr><td>Repo literally named &quot;multi-agent orchestration for Claude Code&quot;</td><td>Dogfooding is the brand</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The likely shape: wshobson&#39;s side runs a scheduled agentic sweep (4h response latency suggests a cron-like trigger) that applies a rubric — small diff + CI-green + NLPM disclosure present + mechanical pattern match — and batches the merges. It may be fully autonomous or click-confirm-batch; from the outside they look the same.</p><p><strong>Our disclosure at the top of each PR body worked.</strong> It&#39;s becoming protocol:</p><div class="language- vp-adaptive-theme"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang"></span><pre class="shiki shiki-themes github-light github-dark vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span>&gt; **Automated audit**: This PR was generated by [NLPM](https://github.com/xiaolai/nlpm-for-claude), a natural language programming linter, running via [claude-code-action](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code-action). Please evaluate the diff on its merits.</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Agentic reviewers on the other side can pattern-match this and route accordingly. Humans can too. We should keep it.</p><h2 id="the-sampling-blind-spot" tabindex="-1">The sampling blind spot <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-sampling-blind-spot" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The sampling blind spot&quot;">​</a></h2><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Scope</th><th>Broken commands</th><th>Broken agents</th><th>Total</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Audit sample (100 files)</td><td>15</td><td>4</td><td>19</td></tr><tr><td>Full repo (282 files)</td><td>50</td><td>7</td><td><strong>57</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Fixed by merged PRs</td><td>13</td><td></td><td>13</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Still broken after merges</strong></td><td><strong>41</strong></td><td><strong>3</strong></td><td><strong>44</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The <code>$MAX_FILES=100</code> cap we added three days ago to survive ARG_MAX on large repos also hid two-thirds of this specific bug. We shipped 5 PRs that fix a real problem — and left 44 files of the same problem untouched. If a human reviewer did this they&#39;d be called negligent.</p><p>The cap isn&#39;t wrong; unbounded file lists break the workflow. But a flat cap is the wrong granularity. <strong>When the audit finds the same bug pattern on &gt;5 files, it should trigger a second pass scoped to just that pattern</strong>, without the 100-file cap, because grepping for one pattern across 500 files is cheap.</p><h2 id="meta-bugs-in-nlpm-this-engagement-surfaced" tabindex="-1">Meta bugs in NLPM this engagement surfaced <a class="header-anchor" href="#meta-bugs-in-nlpm-this-engagement-surfaced" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Meta bugs in NLPM this engagement surfaced&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Three bugs in our own workflows found and fixed while doing this audit. Listed because they will recur on the next big repo if we forget:</p><ol><li><p><strong><code>git checkout --theirs</code> silently dropped workflow&#39;s own data</strong> on push-retry conflicts. The contribute workflow wrote <code>pipeline_prs: [488-492]</code> to the registry; a concurrent push raced; the retry merged in the remote and used <code>--theirs</code> which replaced our new data with the stale remote. Track workflow then couldn&#39;t find the PRs, no <code>case-study-ready</code> label fired, no case study wrote. <strong>Fix (<code>81fbc7d</code>)</strong>: <code>auditor/scripts/resolve-merge-conflicts.sh</code> does jq deep-merge for <code>repos.json</code>, line-union for <code>events.jsonl</code>, <code>--ours</code> for everything else. Applied to audit + contribute + daily-report workflows.</p></li><li><p><strong>Track workflow added <code>case-study-ready</code> label but case-study workflow never fired.</strong> GitHub suppresses <code>issues: labeled</code> events from <code>GITHUB_TOKEN</code> (anti-recursion). Same pattern batch-processor hit for <code>audit-ready</code> last week. <strong>Fix (<code>81fbc7d</code>)</strong>: track now calls <code>gh workflow run auditor-case-study.yml</code> explicitly after labeling. Requires <code>actions: write</code> permission.</p></li><li><p><strong>Case-study workflow had no push retry.</strong> Single <code>git push</code>, no retry loop. Raced my own fix commit and failed; article + cover image abandoned on the destroyed runner. Had to re-dispatch. <strong>Fix (<code>50d2f84</code>)</strong>: same 5-attempt retry loop as the others.</p></li></ol><p>All three are race bugs. The pipeline&#39;s per-workflow isolation masks them in most runs; they surface under load. We should assume every workflow that pushes will race eventually.</p><h2 id="proposals-ranked-by-expected-impact" tabindex="-1">Proposals (ranked by expected impact) <a class="header-anchor" href="#proposals-ranked-by-expected-impact" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Proposals (ranked by expected impact)&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Each has a concrete entry point in the codebase.</p><h3 id="_1-same-pattern-full-scan-trigger" tabindex="-1">1. Same-pattern full-scan trigger <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-same-pattern-full-scan-trigger" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;1. Same-pattern full-scan trigger&quot;">​</a></h3><p><strong>Where</strong>: <code>auditor-audit.yml</code> after the main scoring pass. When any bug category has N&gt;5 instances in the sample, grep the full repo for that category&#39;s signature and append findings. Bound by a grep-based cap (cheap), not a Claude-call cap.</p><p><strong>Example rule</strong>: if <code>BUG-missing-frontmatter</code> count &gt;= 5, run <code>find . -path &#39;*/agents/*.md&#39; -o -path &#39;*/commands/*.md&#39; | while read f; do head -1 &quot;$f&quot; | grep -qx &#39;---&#39; || echo &quot;$f&quot;; done</code> and append each result as a bug finding without re-reading the file.</p><p><strong>Expected impact</strong>: would have caught all 57 files on wshobson/agents in the first pass.</p><h3 id="_2-reviewer-type-tagging-in-the-registry" tabindex="-1">2. Reviewer-type tagging in the registry <a class="header-anchor" href="#_2-reviewer-type-tagging-in-the-registry" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;2. Reviewer-type tagging in the registry&quot;">​</a></h3><p><strong>Where</strong>: <code>auditor/registry/repos.json</code> — new field <code>reviewer_type: agentic | human | hybrid | unknown</code> inferred from signals: PR merged within N seconds of prior PR on same day, template comments, presence of <code>claude-*.yml</code> workflows in target repo, <code>Co-authored-by: Claude</code> in target&#39;s commit history.</p><p><strong>Why it matters</strong>: human-velocity and agent-velocity are different signals. Conflating them makes &quot;merge speed&quot; useless as a prioritization input. Once split, the pipeline can route agentic-reviewer repos to an optimized PR template and prioritize them for backlog drain.</p><h3 id="_3-split-the-maintainer-velocity-metric" tabindex="-1">3. Split the maintainer-velocity metric <a class="header-anchor" href="#_3-split-the-maintainer-velocity-metric" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;3. Split the maintainer-velocity metric&quot;">​</a></h3><p><strong>Where</strong>: registry field <code>maintainer_velocity</code> → replace with <code>maintainer_response_latency</code> (PR-open → first-merge-action) and <code>merge_burst_duration</code> (first-merge → last-merge-of-batch). Both computed by track workflow from existing <code>.prs</code> data.</p><p><strong>Why</strong>: wshobson is 4h 20m on response latency (merely attentive) and 13s on burst (unmistakably agentic). Both numbers are useful; the average is not.</p><h3 id="_4-keep-the-disclosure-at-pr-top-convention-document-it" tabindex="-1">4. Keep the disclosure-at-PR-top convention; document it <a class="header-anchor" href="#_4-keep-the-disclosure-at-pr-top-convention-document-it" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;4. Keep the disclosure-at-PR-top convention; document it&quot;">​</a></h3><p><strong>Where</strong>: <code>skills/nlpm/patterns/</code> — add a pattern doc for agent-to-agent PR disclosure. The current boilerplate works; it should be explicit in the skill, not just in the contribute workflow&#39;s prompt.</p><h3 id="_5-close-the-cross-workflow-race-loophole" tabindex="-1">5. Close the cross-workflow race loophole <a class="header-anchor" href="#_5-close-the-cross-workflow-race-loophole" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;5. Close the cross-workflow race loophole&quot;">​</a></h3><p><strong>Where</strong>: all 5 auditor workflows. Any bot push should assume race. The retry loop is now consistent across audit, contribute, daily-report, case-study. Track still has no retry loop — harmless today because track runs once daily and reads mostly, but should gain the same loop before we ever make track write new data under load.</p><h2 id="remaining-work-on-wshobson-agents" tabindex="-1">Remaining work on wshobson/agents <a class="header-anchor" href="#remaining-work-on-wshobson-agents" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Remaining work on wshobson/agents&quot;">​</a></h2><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Count</th><th>Status</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Bugs found in sample, fixed</td><td>13</td><td>done via PRs 488–492</td></tr><tr><td>Bugs in sample, not fixed in initial PR batch</td><td>6</td><td>unfixed, tracked in issue #493</td></tr><tr><td>Bugs found only in my full scan</td><td>38</td><td>unfixed, documented in <a href="https://github.com/wshobson/agents/discussions/487" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">discussion #487</a></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total still broken</strong></td><td><strong>44</strong></td><td><strong>awaiting maintainer preference on PR structure</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><p>I filed the discussion on upstream the same day; the maintainer has not yet responded. Given the 13-second merge burst on the first batch, the likely ideal shape for the remaining 44 files is <strong>the same per-plugin grouping</strong> — one PR per broken plugin, each small, each mechanical. We have the fix drafted locally; holding until the discussion gets acknowledgment.</p><h2 id="open-questions" tabindex="-1">Open questions <a class="header-anchor" href="#open-questions" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Open questions&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Things this engagement doesn&#39;t answer and shouldn&#39;t claim to:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Was wshobson&#39;s merge fully autonomous, click-confirm, or something else?</strong> We can&#39;t tell from outside. The signals are consistent with scripted merge after agentic review. Could also be a human doing a rapid visual spot-check. Likely doesn&#39;t matter for our purposes — the rubric matters, not the agency.</p></li><li><p><strong>Why did the batch processor leave a 16-minute poll gap?</strong> Audit finished 12:33; contribute started 12:49. That gap is longer than either compute phase. Probably an artifact of the 6-hour batch schedule catching the audit at a suboptimal moment. Worth measuring across all past engagements before adjusting the schedule.</p></li><li><p><strong>Is agentic review the majority case on large Claude Code plugin repos yet, or still an outlier?</strong> wshobson is one data point. If we tag <code>reviewer_type</code> across the registry&#39;s 58 repos we&#39;ll have a base rate to compare.</p></li></ol><h2 id="what-to-do-next-in-order" tabindex="-1">What to do next, in order <a class="header-anchor" href="#what-to-do-next-in-order" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;What to do next, in order&quot;">​</a></h2><ol><li>Land proposal #1 (same-pattern full-scan trigger) — highest leverage; would have changed the wshobson outcome from &quot;fixed 13 of 57&quot; to &quot;fixed 57 of 57&quot; with the same compute budget.</li><li>Land proposal #2 (reviewer-type tagging). Pure observation pass, no workflow changes needed to start — just grep existing registry PR data.</li><li>Draft the 8 per-plugin PRs for the remaining 44 wshobson files, hold until discussion #487 gets a response or until a week passes without one.</li><li>Re-run proposal #1 against the other 55 audited repos and see how many have the same hidden-scope problem. Guess: most.</li></ol>',47)])])}const u=t(n,[["render",s]]);export{g as __pageData,u as default};
